The South African National AIDS Council (SANAC) was established to strengthen political leadership and to serve as a forum for civil society participation in the HIV response. It leads the development and coordination of the National Strategic Plan on HIV, STIs, and TB (NSP). The goal of this agreement is to improve the coordinated response of the HIV and TB epidemics with the objectives that:  
1. Prevention, care, and treatment strategies reflect the South African epidemics for maximum impact; 
2. Multi-sectorial, civil society, and external resources are aligned to the National Strategic Plan and are channeled efficiently; 
3. Proper oversight is administered by the Country Coordinating Mechanism (CCM) which is responsible for Global Fund resources for South Africa; and 
4. South Africa is able to monitor, evaluate, and report on the status of the HIV epidemic and response. SANAC operates at a national level but works closely with provincial AIDS councils that also work with district and local AIDS councils. Cost efficiency is not applicable to this agreement as they are not providing service delivery. PEPFAR funding is covering several specific activities which are already cost efficient. SANAC is already primarily government funded. With a reduction in PEPFAR funds over time, continuing activities will have to be funded either through the SAG or through the Global Fund. Select M&E output and outcome indicators include: Participation on the PFIP prevention work stream; NSP mid-term review completed; and improved implementation and spending of Global Fund grantees. SANAC award will commence in April 2014. Although it will only receive $200,000 in FY 2014 funds, additional central Global Fund Initiative funds will be used to supplement FY 2014 funds.

Due to its geographic location, Aceh is highly susceptible to natural disasters, hence the ability of local and national government agencies to respond rapidly and effectively to emergency situations is critical. The objectives of this special operation pursued WFP Strategic Objective 5, through the development of emergency preparedness and response capacities of Aceh's Disaster Management Agencies (BPBA) and the district Disaster Management Agencies (BPBD).

In 2012, the operation focused on five specific disaster risk reduction activities;

1. developing emergency preparedness and response;
2. implementing emergency preparedness and response training programmes;
3. augmenting coordination within the disaster risk reduction (DRR) community at a provincial level.
4. managing assets; and 
5. developing a radio communication network for emergency coordination in Aceh.

Tijdens de 12e Réunion Technique Mixte (RTM), gehouden op 7 december 2009 in Dakar, werd er een Indicatief Samenwerkingsprogramma (ISP) 2010-2013 overeengekomen voor een bedrag van 52,5 MEUR. In dit nieuwe ISP werd voor het uitvoeren van het Plan National de Développement Sanitaire (PNDS 2008-2019) 21 MEUR ingeschreven. De gezondheidszorg werd er, na een afwezigheid van 3 jaar, opnieuw erkend als de eerste sociale prioritaire sector van onze gouvernementele samenwerking. De Belgische steun ging hier bestaan uit 2 interventies en verdeeld over de volgende 3 componenten:
-	de steun aan de institutionele versterking op centraal vlak en aan de capaciteitsopbouw op regionaal vlak;
-	de inbreng om het gezondheidszorgsysteem op districtniveau te verstevigen;
-	de inbreng om de bescherming tegen gezondheidsrisico¿s in de informele sector uit te breiden.
De voorliggende interventie Appui à la gouvernance sanitaire centrale et des 5 régions médicales (PAGOSAN) voor een bedrag van 5 000 000 , uitgevoerd in regie van BTC en medebeheer gedurende 4 jaar, focust op de eerste component.

The Twinning Partnership will continue to support the development of mid-level health care workers and strengthen pre-service training institutions and regulatory councils. Support will continue for partnerships between U.S. based organizations and South African Universities (north-south partnerships) and between in-country and regional organizations (south-south partnerships and south-south-north partnerships) to strengthen human and organizational capacity. The objectives of the partnerships are to strengthen health systems in South Africa through:
 Expanding the pool of trained providers, managers, and allied health staff delivering quality HIV/AIDS services;
 Strengthening organization structures and systems;
 Supporting limited infrastructure enhancements;
 Facilitating private sector engagement through volunteerism; and
 Working in support of in-country Government strategic plans and OGAC-supported PEPFAR team priorities.
